\q2 \w make|strong="G4160"\w* \w His|strong="G1722"\w* \w paths|strong="G5147"\w* \w straight|strong="G2117"\w*.\f + \fr 3:4 \ft The Hebrew text of Isa. 40:3 has “in the desert” here, making it overtly parallel to “in the wilderness”, so both are part of what the ‘voice’ is saying.\f*
\q1 
\v 5 \w Every|strong="G3956"\w* \w ravine|strong="G5327"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w filled|strong="G4137"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w*,
\q2 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w mountain|strong="G3735"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w hill|strong="G3735"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* leveled;\f + \fr 3:5 \ft That is, where the highway passes, not all over the place; just like modern superhighways.\f*
\q1 \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w crooked|strong="G4646"\w* parts \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w roads|strong="G3598"\w* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* straightened \w out|strong="G2532"\w*,
\q2 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w rough|strong="G5138"\w* parts \w will|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* smoothed \w out|strong="G2532"\w*;
\q1 
\v 6 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w flesh|strong="G4561"\w*\f + \fr 3:6 \ft That's what the Text says. I resist the temptation to limit the reference to people, because the animals will also see it (Isaiah 11:6-9). In Genesis 6:17 “all flesh” clearly includes the animals.\f* \w will|strong="G2316"\w* \w see|strong="G3708"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w salvation|strong="G4992"\w* \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*.’ ”
\s1 “Brood of vipers!”
\p 
\v 7 \w Then|strong="G3767"\w* \w he|strong="G3588"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w crowds|strong="G3793"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G3195"\w* \w out|strong="G1607"\w* \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w be|strong="G3195"\w* baptized \w by|strong="G5259"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*: “\w You|strong="G5210"\w* sons \w of|strong="G5259"\w* poisonous snakes!\f + \fr 3:7 \ft We don't know the precise type of snake, except that it was presumably poisonous. The Text has ‘offsprings’, plural, which doesn't make very good English, so I put ‘sons’. From Matthew 3:7 we may conclude that he was mainly referring to Pharisees and Sadducees (who had come to evaluate what was happening, but did not themselves submit to the baptism; they would not want to admit that they had sin to confess).\f* \w Who|strong="G5101"\w* tipped \w you|strong="G5210"\w* off \w to|strong="G3004"\w* \w flee|strong="G5343"\w* \w from|strong="G5259"\w* \w the|strong="G3588"\w* \w coming|strong="G3195"\w* \w wrath|strong="G3709"\w*?
\v 8 \w Well|strong="G2532"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w produce|strong="G4160"\w* \w fruits|strong="G2590"\w* befitting \w repentance|strong="G3341"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* \it even\it* begin \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w among|strong="G1722"\w* \w yourselves|strong="G1438"\w*, ‘\w We|strong="G3754"\w* \w have|strong="G2192"\w* Abraham \w as|strong="G1722"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w*,’ \w because|strong="G3754"\w* \w I|strong="G2532"\w* \w say|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w that|strong="G3754"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w able|strong="G1410"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w raise|strong="G1453"\w* \w up|strong="G1453"\w* \w children|strong="G5043"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* Abraham \w from|strong="G1537"\w* \w these|strong="G3778"\w* \w stones|strong="G3037"\w*!\f + \fr 3:8 \ft To be born into a Christian family is certainly an advantage, but does not guarantee your eternal destiny. God has no ‘grandchildren’; you must believe into the Lord Jesus Christ to become God's child.\f*
\v 9 \w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w now|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* axe \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w laid|strong="G2749"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w root|strong="G4491"\w* \w of|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w trees|strong="G1186"\w*;\f + \fr 3:9 \ft The Messiah was about to be introduced and to begin His public ministry; among other things He would condemn the Pharisees and other ‘snakes’—‘thrown into the fire’ refers to their eternal destiny.\f* \w so|strong="G3767"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w*, \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w tree|strong="G1186"\w* \w not|strong="G3361"\w* \w producing|strong="G4160"\w* \w good|strong="G2570"\w* \w fruit|strong="G2590"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w cut|strong="G1581"\w* \w down|strong="G1581"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* thrown \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w fire|strong="G4442"\w*.”
\s1 “What shall we do?”
\p 
\v 10 \w So|strong="G3767"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G3793"\w*\f + \fr 3:10 \ft The Text has ‘crowds’.\f* started \w asking|strong="G1905"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w then|strong="G3767"\w* \w must|strong="G4160"\w* \w we|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*?”
\v 11 \w In|strong="G2532"\w* answer \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “\w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w two|strong="G1417"\w* \w coats|strong="G5509"\w*,\f + \fr 3:11 \ft Literally, ‘tunics’.\f* \w let|strong="G1161"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w share|strong="G3330"\w* \w with|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w none|strong="G3361"\w*; \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w has|strong="G2192"\w* \w food|strong="G1033"\w* \w should|strong="G3588"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w* \w likewise|strong="G3668"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:11 \ft The verb ‘share’ is an aorist imperative, implying a one time event—you give the extra coat, but get to keep one. The verb ‘do’ is a present imperative, implying a continuing action—food is to be shared all the time.\f*
\v 12 \w Well|strong="G2532"\w* \w even|strong="G2532"\w* \w tax|strong="G5057"\w* \w collectors|strong="G5057"\w* \w came|strong="G2064"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* baptized \w by|strong="G2532"\w* \w him|strong="G4160"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w him|strong="G4160"\w*, “\w Teacher|strong="G1320"\w*, \w what|strong="G5101"\w* \w must|strong="G4160"\w* \w we|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*?”
\v 13 \w So|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G1161"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “Don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* charge \w more|strong="G4119"\w* \w than|strong="G3844"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* determined \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:13 \ft Right on. The tax collectors were hated, among other things, because they usually added a percentage for themselves.\f*
\v 14 \w So|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w soldiers|strong="G4754"\w* started \w asking|strong="G1905"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w too|strong="G2532"\w*: “\w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w about|strong="G4314"\w* \w us|strong="G3004"\w*? \w What|strong="G5101"\w* \w must|strong="G4160"\w* \w we|strong="G2249"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*?” \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w said|strong="G3004"\w* \w to|strong="G4314"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, “Don'\w t|strong="G3588"\w* extort \w or|strong="G2532"\w* harass \w anyone|strong="G3367"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G2532"\w* \w content|strong="G4160"\w* \w with|strong="G4314"\w* \w your|strong="G2532"\w* \w wages|strong="G3800"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:14 \ft Right on again. Soldiers would frequently try to ‘supplement’ their wages.\f*
\s1 “A greater One is coming”
\p 
\v 15 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w as|strong="G1722"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* expectant \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w reasoning|strong="G1260"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w their|strong="G2532"\w* \w hearts|strong="G2588"\w* \w concerning|strong="G4012"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w*, \w whether|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w just|strong="G2532"\w* \w might|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Messiah|strong="G5547"\w*,
\v 16 \w John|strong="G2491"\w* anticipated \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*: “\w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* baptizing \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w water|strong="G5204"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w One|strong="G3739"\w* \w mightier|strong="G2478"\w* \w than|strong="G2478"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w coming|strong="G2064"\w*, \w whose|strong="G3739"\w* \w sandal|strong="G5266"\w* straps \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w worthy|strong="G2425"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w untie|strong="G3089"\w*. \nd \w He|strong="G2532"\w*\nd* \w will|strong="G1510"\w* baptize \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w with|strong="G1722"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w fire|strong="G4442"\w*;\f + \fr 3:16 \ft I suppose that this was fulfilled at Pentecost, although it is also true that all our works will be tested by fire (1 Corinthians 3:12-15).\f*
\v 17 \w whose|strong="G3739"\w* \w winnowing|strong="G4425"\w* shovel \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* \w hand|strong="G5495"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w thoroughly|strong="G1245"\w* clean \w out|strong="G2532"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* threshing floor \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w gather|strong="G4863"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w wheat|strong="G4621"\w* \w into|strong="G1519"\w* \w His|strong="G1519"\w* barn, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w He|strong="G2532"\w* \w will|strong="G2532"\w* \w burn|strong="G2618"\w* \w up|strong="G1519"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* chaff \w with|strong="G1722"\w* unquenchable \w fire|strong="G4442"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:17 \ft “Unquenchable fire” is a clear reference to the Lake; recall that there is always more chaff than grain, but the chaff is also part of the wheat plant. I suspect that most churches have more chaff than grain.\f*
\s1 John is imprisoned—an historical aside
\p 
\v 18 (\w Indeed|strong="G2532"\w*, \w with|strong="G2532"\w* \w many|strong="G4183"\w* \w other|strong="G2087"\w* \w exhortations|strong="G3870"\w* \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w well|strong="G2532"\w* \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w kept|strong="G2992"\w* \w on|strong="G3767"\w* \w preaching|strong="G2097"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w*;
\v 19 \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w Herod|strong="G2264"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w tetrarch|strong="G5076"\w*—\w being|strong="G2532"\w* \w reproved|strong="G1651"\w* \w by|strong="G5259"\w* \w him|strong="G3588"\w* \w concerning|strong="G4012"\w* \w Herodias|strong="G2266"\w*, \w his|strong="G3956"\w* brother's \w wife|strong="G1135"\w*, \w as|strong="G1161"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w about|strong="G4012"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w wicked|strong="G4190"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w that|strong="G3739"\w* \w Herod|strong="G2264"\w* perpetrated\f + \fr 3:19 \ft A coward John was not!\f*—
\v 20 \w added|strong="G4369"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w*: \w he|strong="G2532"\w* \w actually|strong="G2532"\w* \w locked|strong="G2623"\w* \w John|strong="G2491"\w* \w up|strong="G2623"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w his|strong="G3956"\w* \w prison|strong="G5438"\w*.)
\s1 Jesus is baptized
\p 
\v 21 \w Now|strong="G1161"\w* \w when|strong="G1161"\w* \w all|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w people|strong="G2992"\w* \w were|strong="G3588"\w* baptized, \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w*, \w having|strong="G2532"\w* \w been|strong="G1096"\w* baptized \w also|strong="G2532"\w*, \w was|strong="G1096"\w* \w praying|strong="G4336"\w*, \w when|strong="G1161"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w heaven|strong="G3772"\w* \w was|strong="G1096"\w* opened
\v 22 \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G1722"\w* \w Holy|strong="G4151"\w* \w Spirit|strong="G4151"\w* \w descended|strong="G2597"\w* \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w bodily|strong="G4984"\w* \w form|strong="G1491"\w* \w like|strong="G5613"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \w dove|strong="G4058"\w* \it and rested\it* \w upon|strong="G1909"\w* \w Him|strong="G3588"\w*, \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w a|strong="G1096"\w* \bd \w Voice|strong="G5456"\w*\bd* \w came|strong="G1096"\w* \w out|strong="G1537"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w heaven|strong="G3772"\w* saying, “\w You|strong="G4771"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w my|strong="G1722"\w* beloved \w Son|strong="G5207"\w*; \w in|strong="G1722"\w* \w you|strong="G4771"\w* \w I|strong="G1473"\w* \w am|strong="G1510"\w* always \w well|strong="G2532"\w* \w pleased|strong="G2106"\w*.”\f + \fr 3:22 \ft The Trinity is manifested here, which would be an important confirmation for Jesus.\f*
\ms1 Mary's genealogy\f + \fr 3:23 \ft The genealogy interrupts the chronological sequence of the narrative, which resumes at 4:1.\f*
\p 
\v 23 (Beginning \it His ministry\it* \w at|strong="G3588"\w* \w about|strong="G5613"\w* \w thirty|strong="G5144"\w* \w years|strong="G2094"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w age|strong="G2094"\w*, \w being|strong="G1510"\w* (\w so|strong="G2532"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w supposed|strong="G3543"\w*) \w a|strong="G5613"\w* \w son|strong="G5207"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w*,
\q1 \w Jesus|strong="G2424"\w* Himself\f + \fr 3:23 \ft There are several unusual grammatical features in the Greek text of this verse, which has been badly translated by every version I have seen; resulting in contradictions and errors of fact. Here is the Greek, for those who can read it: Και αυτος ἦν ὁ Ιησους, ὡσει ετων τριακοντα αρχομενος, ων ὡς ενομιζετο υἱος Ιωσηφ, του Ηλει, του Ματθαν, του Λευι, του Μελχι,… There are four words here that invite special attention: και, αυτος, ἦν and ὡς. Since verse 22 ends with a statement from the Father at Jesus' baptism, it is clear that verse 23 begins another section. But the conjunction that signals the transition is και and not δε, as one would expect—this means that ‘Jesus’ continues as the topic. But in that event, how does one explain the personal pronoun αυτος, the more so in such an emphatic position? If the author's purpose was simply to register Jesus as a son of Joseph, as many suppose, why did he not just write και ὁ Ιησους ἦν υἱος Ιωσηφ, etc.?\fp But then, why write ὡς ενομιζετο? It seems to me that the normal meaning of “as was supposed” is to affirm that Jesus was in fact Joseph's son; but that is precisely what Jesus \bd was \nd not\nd*\bd*. Luke has already made clear that Jesus' real Father was the Holy Spirit—1:34-35, 43, 45; 2:49. So what Luke is really saying is that although the people supposed Jesus to be Joseph's son, He actually had a different lineage—we should translate “so it was supposed”. (Recall that a faithful and loyal translation seeks to transmit correctly the meaning intended by the \nd author\nd*.)\fp The verb ἦν is the only independent one in the whole paragraph, verses 23-38. Is it working with the participle αρχομενος in a periphrastic construction? That appears to be the tendency of the eclectic text that places the participle right after ‘Jesus’ (following about 1% of the Greek manuscripts, of objectively inferior quality), which makes Jesus out to be in fact Joseph's son. It seems to me to be far more natural to take the participial clauses as being circumstantial: “beginning at about thirty years of age” and “being (so it was supposed) a son of Joseph”. Setting those two clauses aside, the independent clause that remains is ἦν ὁ Ιησους του Ηλει, “Jesus was of Eli”.\fp The participle ‘beginning’ requires an object, that the Text leaves implicit; from the context it seems clear that we may supply ‘His ministry’, or some such thing, which is why most versions do so. I suggest the following rendering: “Beginning \it His ministry\it* at about thirty years of age, being (so it was supposed) a son of Joseph, Jesus was actually of Eli, of Mathan, of Levi…” I take it that the emphatic pronoun αυτος heightens the contrast between what the people imagined and the reality. Jesus was a grandson of Eli, Mary's father—Luke gives the genealogy of Jesus through His mother, while Matthew gives it through His stepfather.\fp The eclectic text gives our verse a different wording: και αυτος ἦν Ιησους αρχομενος ὡσει ετων τριακοντα, ων υἱος, ὡς ενομιζετο, Ιωσηφ του Ηλι του Μαθθατ του Λευι του Μελκι,… The RSV translates it like this: “Jesus, when he began his ministry, was about thirty years of age, being the son (as was supposed) of Joseph, the son of Heli, the son of Matthat,…” Is not the normal meaning of this rendering that Jesus was in fact the son of Joseph? However, every version that I recall seeing has “Joseph, the son of Heli”, which directly contradicts Matthew, “Jacob begot Joseph”. The word ‘son’ (without the article) occurs only with Joseph, although most versions supply it on down the genealogy. But Luke is precisely correct in not using it, because it would not hold for the first and last names in the list—Eli did not beget Jesus (nor Joseph) and God did not beget Adam. So then, properly understood Luke does not contradict Matthew (with reference to Joseph's father), nor does he affirm an error of fact (with reference to Jesus' father).\f* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G5207"\w* \w Eli|strong="G2242"\w*,\f + \fr 3:23 \ft All published Bibles that I have seen add ‘son’ or ‘the son’ to each prepositional phrase in the genealogy, but Luke did not write that—from ‘Eli’ to ‘God’ there is no ‘son’. Why not? I do not know, I was not there, but with both Eli and God the word would have a different meaning than with the rest of the names in the list. Adam could be called a ‘son’ of God by creation, but not procreation. I take it that Eli was Mary's father, and thus the maternal grandfather of Jesus, so here also ‘son’ would have a different meaning. For all that, through Mary and Eli Jesus received some of David's genes, so He was literally a descendant of David, through his son Nathan.\f*
\q2 
\v 24 \w of|strong="G3588"\w* Matthan,\f + \fr 3:24 \ft There is considerable confusion among the Greek manuscripts as to the spelling of all these names. I have generally just followed the spelling we are used to (since the meaning is not affected), but not always.\f* \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w Levi|strong="G3017"\w*, \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w Melchi|strong="G3197"\w*, \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w Janna|strong="G2388"\w*, \w of|strong="G3588"\w* \w Joseph|strong="G2501"\w*,
\q1 
