\v 41 \w Nevertheless|strong="G4133"\w*, \w give|strong="G1325"\w* \w what|strong="G3588"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* possible \w as|strong="G2532"\w* \w alms|strong="G1654"\w*; \w then|strong="G2532"\w* \w indeed|strong="G2532"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w things|strong="G3956"\w* \w are|strong="G1510"\w* \w clean|strong="G2513"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w*.\f + \fr 11:41 \ft At first glance this statement seems difficult, but because they were filled with greed, for them to give away as much as possible would represent a major change in their values. Zacchaeus offers a case in point: the Lord Himself declared that he was saved (Luke 19:8-9).\f*
\p 
\v 42 “\w But|strong="G1161"\w* \w woe|strong="G3759"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* \w Pharisees|strong="G5330"\w*! \w You|strong="G5210"\w* tithe \w mint|strong="G2238"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w rue|strong="G4076"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w every|strong="G3956"\w* \w herb|strong="G3001"\w*, \w but|strong="G1161"\w* \w you|strong="G5210"\w* ignore \w justice|strong="G2920"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* love \w of|strong="G2316"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w*. \nd \w These|strong="G3778"\w*\nd* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w was|strong="G3588"\w* \w necessary|strong="G1163"\w* \w to|strong="G2532"\w* \w do|strong="G4160"\w*, \w without|strong="G3361"\w* \w leaving|strong="G3588"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* undone.
